        text: "On the second floor of the fifth entrance was the home of the great Ukrainian lyric poet Volodymyr Sosiura, the author of the famous patriotic line Love Ukraine. He was the main cupid of the Ukrainian SSR. His poems gave life to love in the 1930s, fed it, and inspired it. Romantic evenings often looked like Sosiura poetry readings, and young people scribbled down his verses and recited them to each other.\n\nHe had a complicated character, famous for endless love affairs and a complete lack of common sense. Although he earned some of the highest fees of any writer, he lived in poverty. The family slept on the floor, there was almost no furniture, and arguments and fights were a regular part of home life. He spent every ruble on fun and on friends who took advantage of him. That wild way of life led to repeated breakdowns and, in turn, to being sent to a psychiatric hospital again and again. Even though the NKVD had a conflict with Sosiura, they let him live.\n\nThe Ukrainian artists killed by the Soviet government in the 1920s and 1930s are known as the Executed Renaissance.\n\nThe last apartment, number sixty eight in the fifth entrance, belonged to the master of Ukrainian drama, an outstanding director and innovator, Les Kurbas. He gave his last breath to the Berezil Theater and spent day and night there. As a result, he usually came home either very early in the morning or late at night. Despite the shared artistic calling, Kurbas had a cold relationship with Dovzhenko, and the feeling was mutual. Mykola Kulish, the famous playwright, was his best friend. The two seemed made for each other. Kulish wrote the plays, and Kurbas brought them to life on stage, a perfect pair. Volodymyr Kulish remembered that the evenings when his father came to Berezil to read his works were a real celebration. Even though he was not an actor, the playwright embodied the characters on stage in ways even trained actors recognized, and Kurbas himself borrowed those tricks in later productions.\n\nWhen Kulish was arrested, Kurbas stayed a loyal friend. None of the party suggestions could tempt him to turn his back on the enemy of the people or on Kulish controversial views. For the first time in his life, Les Kurbas dropped his usual reserve and respect, and spoke about the party leadership in blunt, vulgar terms. That moment became his own death sentence. In October 1933, the Berezil Theater, the heart of Kurbas world, was shut down. While in exile, the director kept working creatively, running the central theater of the White Sea Baltic Canal, a ship canal in Russia, near the Vedmezha Hora, or Bear Mountain, camp, where he staged plays for half a year. Stepping on a stage for the first time in a long while, Kurbas said with tears in his eyes, My God, a theater.\n\nA striking detail: at the age of twenty six, Les Kurbas, heartbroken from unanswered love, tried to take his own life and shot himself in the chest. He somehow survived, but the bullet stayed in his heart for the rest of his days."
