        text: "Despite the dark fame Slovo carries today, at the start it was an island of creative freedom, a bright spot against the gray backdrop of Soviet Kharkiv. The residents paid close attention to fashion. When one of the slovians showed up with a new piece of clothing or brought back some unusual item from abroad, the others quickly copied it as best they could.\n\nThe Slovo house could fairly be called a dense concentration of talent per square meter.\n\nMany of the writers loved to hunt. They liked being out in nature, where there were no extra ears, and they could talk openly. When the men came back from a trip, they brought plenty of funny stories with them. The author remembered, for example, his father coming home one day with three ducks and a snipe. That evening, he told grand stories about heroically hunting down his big game. When his wife started cleaning the birds, she found a tag that read Ukrptakhprom Kharkiv, the local poultry farm, on each duck. The playwright was not thrown off. He said the tag was a standard way of marking birds for later identification.\n\nSports was another shared passion. The residents built a volleyball court in the yard, where friendly neighborhood tournaments were held. It was not just for the kids. Older and younger slovians played side by side, putting age differences aside for a while. Over time, the writers of Slovo became quite good at volleyball. When theater troupes came to Kharkiv on tour, they organized large tournaments. The games usually ran until sunset, and the players headed out for a beer together afterward.\n\nIn winter, the court was flooded and turned into a skating rink, and crowds of noisy Slovo residents came out to skate. Mykola Khvylovy was a real artist on the ice. He could pull off the giant steps and other elegant figure skating moves."
